'She has played her part in history and deserves a happy ending - not rotting at the bottom of a river.

'The boat is an important piece of British military and naval history and should not be allowed to just sink without trace. But it’s proved impossible to raise her.'

The Royal Navy experts, based at Faslane on the Clyde, were using special buoyancy bags in an attempt to lift the vessel.

Mr McCann said: 'We don’t know what’s going to happen now. There’s nothing more we can do without funding.'

The Skylark was among the smallest of the 'little ships' flotilla from 1940 which responded to the urgent call from Winston Churchill to rescue the Allied forces.

