Her capacity was officially 90 passengers, but it managed to make four cross-Channel return trips carrying 150 exhausted and wounded soldiers each time.

The 50-foot vessel was built in 1927 as a pleasure cruiser in Poole, Dorset. It then spent years ferrying trippers around Brighton harbour.

The boat was commandeered after war was declared and it became a shallow water minesweeper.

It was also used to place anti-invasion obstacles around Poole harbour.

After the war, the vessel changed hands several times, moving gradually north before settling on Loch Lomond.

